1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 {The point of this move is to avoid the development 
of White's knight to e2 in the exchange variation. This Botvinnik invention is 
still considered as most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. Its idea 
is not to block the f-pawn so as to be able to build a big centre by playng f3 
and e4. Now if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation he will have to 
make some concessions.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 {Now Black's plan is to play Bd6, 
exchanging the active Bf4. Later he will try to put the bishop on f5.} 6. Qc2 
Bd6 {The well-known move liberates e7 for the Ng8, thus aiding the main idea of 
Bf5} 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. e3 Ne7 {With the idea of ...Bf5, so White prevents it with 
his next move.} 9. Bd3 b6 {Since getting to f5 is difficult, Black chooses an 
alternative development for the Bc8.} 10. Nf3 Ba6 11. O-O Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Nd7 13. 
e4 O-O {Evacuating the king.} 14. e5 Qe6 {Blockading the pawn so that it cannot 
advance after Black attacks it with ...f6.} 15. Rae1 f6 $1 {This equalises as 
White cannot preserve the pawn on e5.} 16. exf6 Qxf6 17. Re3 Nf5 18. Re2 Rae8 
{Contesting the e-file.} 19. Rfe1 Rxe2 20. Rxe2 *

