1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 {The point of this move is to avoid the development 
of White's knight to e2 in the Exchange Variation. This Botvinnik invention is 
still considered as most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. Its idea 
is not to block the f-pawn so as to be able to build a big centre by playng f3 
and e4. Now if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation he will have to 
make some concessions.} 4. Qc2 Nf6 5. cxd5 Nxd5 {Taking with the knight is 
important, because taking with the pawn would lead to the desired Carlsbad 
structure when after Bg5 White can develop the Ng1 to e2.} 6. Nf3 O-O {with a 
good position for Black, who follows up with Nd7 and c5 or b6} 7. g3 Nxc3 {This 
is based on very concrete lines, Black is taking advantage of his lead in 
development (his king is already castled) and starts an attack against the pawn 
on d4.} 8. Qxc3 Nc6 $1 {Attacking d4 and planning to follow up with ...Bf6} 9. 
a3 Bf6 {Not only does the d4-pawn hang, Black also wants to push ...e5. The move 
10 e3 is bad not only visually, but also tactically, as it fails to 10...e5! 11 
de Bg4 and White's position falls apart, for example 12 Bg2 Bf3 13 Bf3 Ne5 with 
the threat of ...Nf3 winning the queen.} 10. Be3 e5 $1 {A small tactic, the pawn 
is indirectly defended.} 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Qd5 {A double attack on h1 and 
e5, if White moves the rook then by taking ...Be5 Black will be much better 
since the White king will be left without castling, so White must try to muddy 
the waters.} 13. exf6 Qxh1 14. Qe5 {Taking on g7 is unfortunately not good for 
White since after Rd8 the White king cannot escape from e1 and Black has the 
winning threat of ...Bh3.} Qxh2 {It is important to cover h6, in order to avoid 
being mated by Qg5, forcing ...g6, and then Qh6.} 15. Rd1 {With ideas like 
Rd4-h4.} Be6 {Finishing development and controlling d5, an important square for 
the ...Qh1-d5 maneuver.} 16. Rd4 {Threatening Rh4.} Qh1 {With the idea to 
counter Rh4 by ...Qd5, hence the importance of Be6.} 17. Qg5 Qh6 {Forcing an 
endgame.} 18. Qxh6 gxh6 19. Bxh6 Rfd8 {With an unclear game, but if anybody it 
is Black who will try to win this.} *

