1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 {The point of this move is to avoid the development 
of White's knight to e2 in the Exchange Variation. This Botvinnik invention is 
still considered as most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. Its idea 
is not to block the f-pawn so as to be able to build a big centre by playng f3 
and e4. Now if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation he will have to 
make some concessions.} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {Leads to the normal position of the QGD and 
here the exchange variation is rather harmless for Black, who can comfortably 
develop his Bc8 to f5.} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 c6 7. e3 Bf5 {And black is equal 
here since he managed to develop the Bc8 actively on f5.} 8. Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 
Nbd7 {Connecting the knights, so in case White takes on f6 Black can retake with 
a knight.} 10. O-O O-O {This is very similar to 7 Qc2 g6 8 e3 Bf5, here Black's 
pawn is still on g7 rather than on g6. The manner of treating the position 
remains the same though - Black can successfully defend against the typical 
minority attack, as shown in the following game by Kramnik.} 11. Rab1 a5 
{Preventing b4 and when White prepares it with a3 then the exchange on b4 will 
open the a-file for Black.} 12. a3 Ne4 {This knight jump is based on the tactic 
that the Bg5 is attacked so White cannot take twice on e4. If White takes on e7 
then after Black takes with the queen then the Ne4 is defended twice.} 13. Bxe7 
Qxe7 14. b4 $6 b5 $1 {A very important move. Not only does it prevent the 
typical minority attack with b5, but also establishes a strong outpost on c4 for 
one of the knights (Nd6-c4 or Nb6-c4) .} 15. Qc2 axb4 {Opening the a-file to 
activate the Ra8.} 16. axb4 Nd6 $15 {Avoiding the exchange as both Black's 
knights have excellent outposts, so it's better to keep them both.} 17. Rb3 Nb6 
18. Ne5 Rfc8 {The other rook is useful on the a-file. The Ne5 can easily be 
kicked with ...f6, so this is only temporary.} 19. Nd3 Nbc4 {Black is better 
here, as he has successfully plugged the queenside and can now turn his 
attention to the centre and the kingside. In the game Nikolic,P (2635) 
-Kramnik,V (2790) Monte Carlo 1998, which Black won in great style, he went on 
to play ...Re8, ...g6, ...h5, ...Qg5, ...Ra7-e7, ...Nf5 and eventually 
sacrificed on e3!} *

