1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 {The point of this move is to avoid the development 
of White's knight to e2 in the Exchange Variation. This Botvinnik invention is 
still considered as most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. Its idea 
is not to block the f-pawn so as to be able to build a big centre by playng f3 
and e4. Now if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation he will have to 
make some concessions.} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {Leads to the normal position of the QGD and 
here the exchange variation is rather harmless for Black, who can comfortably 
develop his Bc8 to f5.} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 c6 7. Qc2 g6 $1 {It is vital to 
secure the exit of the bishop to f5!} 8. e3 Bf5 {Is similar to the game 
Nikolic-Kramnik from the line 7 e3 Bf5} 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 {The same 
idea, to be able to retake on f6 with a knight.} 11. O-O O-O 12. Rab1 {The 
traditional minority attack doesn't bring White anything. In fact, it can easily 
lead him into trouble, for example:} a5 13. Qc2 Re8 {The difference with the 
Kramnik game is that here ...Ne4 would be bad because White can escape with the 
bishop on h6, gaining tempo and winning a pawn after taking on e4 twice. 
Therefore with the rook move Black prepares the knight jump to e4.} 14. a3 Ne4 
$1 {Now this works.} 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. b4 Nd6 {Again we see the same idea as in 
the Kramnik game. Once White has weakened the c4-square by advancing the b-pawn 
Black immediately takes advantage of it.} 17. Nd2 axb4 18. axb4 b5 $15 {And 
Black is again better as the ideas are the same as in the game Nikolic-Kramnik, 
The game we've been following is Lopez Rodriguez,F (2153) -Korneev,O (2649) Dos 
Hermanas 2006, also nicely won by Black.} *

