still considered as most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. Its idea 
is not to block the f-pawn so as to be able to build a big centre by playng f3 
and e4. Now if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation he will have to 
make some concessions.} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {Leads to the normal position of the QGD and 
here the exchange variation is rather harmless for Black, who can comfortably 
develop his Bc8 to f5.} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 c6 7. Qc2 g6 $1 {It is vital to 
secure the exit of the bishop to f5!} 8. e4 {The only way for White to try for 
more} dxe4 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Qxe4+ Kf8 {It is possible to cover with the queen, 
but the king will quickly move to g7 so the loss of castling rights is not an 
issue here.} 11. Bc4 Bf5 {Winning tempo to speed up the development.} 12. Qf4 
Qe7+ {Forcing White to go back with the bishop.} 13. Be2 h5 {Preventing g4} 14. 
O-O Nd7 {Black has smooth development and with the bishop pair can be optimistic 
about the middlegame} 15. Rad1 Kg7 {Finally connecting the rooks.} 16. a3 
{Preventing possible Qb4 ideas} Rhe8 17. Rfe1 Qd8 {With the nice idea of Qb8-d6 
as the queen on d6 will be centralised and if if White takes on b8 then the 
endgame with a pair of bishops and an isolated queen's pawn for White would be 
very pleasant for Black.} 18. d5 Qb6 {The queen changes the trajectory now, 
attacking b2 with good counterplay.} 19. dxc6 bxc6 {Taking with the queen is 
impossible because of Bb5 and Black will be in trouble, but taking with the pawn 
is good because the pawn controls the important d5-square, thus limiting the 
Nc3. Now the pawn on b2 is hanging and Black's bishops are very active in an 
open position.} 20. Nd4 Bxd4 {Again exchanging everything on d4 is good for 
Black as in the endgame he can use the open b-file to create counterplay against 
the b2-pawn.} 21. Qxd4+ Qxd4 22. Rxd4 Nc5 {Threatening ...Nd3.} 23. Kf1 Rab8 
{Attacking b2.} 24. b4 Nb3 {Gaining a tempo by attacking the rook as on the next 
move Black will get rid of the c6-pawn and will equalise the position 
completely.} 25. Rd6 c5 $11 *

