still considered as most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. Its idea 
is not to block the f-pawn so as to be able to build a big centre by playng f3 
and e4. Now if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation he will have to 
make some concessions.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 {Now Black's plan is to play Bd6, 
exchanging the active Bf4. Later he will also try to put the bishop on f5.} 6. 
Qc2 Bd6 {The well-known move liberates e7 for the Ng8, thus aiding the main idea 
of Bf5.} 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. e3 Ne7 {With the idea of ...Bf5, so White prevents it 
with his next move.} 9. Bd3 b6 {Since getting to f5 is difficult, Black choses 
an alternative development for the Bc8} 10. e4 {Suggested by Kasparov, but 
easily defused.} dxe4 11. Nxe4 Qb4+ {Taking the pawn is dangerous, so better to 
gain time by giving a check and exchanging the Bd3 next.} 12. Nd2 Ba6 {Again 
taking the pawn is dangerous, so Black consistently follows the plan to exchange 
the light-squared bishops.} 13. Ngf3 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 O-O {Evacuating the king in 
order not to run into trouble along the e-file} 15. O-O Nd7 {Black finished 
development and has a solid and flexible position. White needs to be careful not 
to end up worse with the isolated pawn on d4.} 16. Rfe1 Nd5 {Blockading the 
isolated pawn with a very good position for Black.} *

